    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. To clarify, an escrow agent is responsible for holding funds and documents until certain conditions are met in a real estate transaction. Their primary duties include:\n\n1. Receiving and holding earnest money from the buyer until the closing date.\n2. Paying real estate taxes and insurance premiums on behalf of the property owner.\n3. Distributing funds for other expenses, such as homeowner association fees, if applicable.\n4. Ensuring that the seller fulfills their obligations, such as completing repairs or providing access to the property.\n5. Coordinating the transfer of ownership and recording the deed with the county recorder's office.\n\nThe escrow agent acts as an intermediary between the buyer and seller, ensuring that both parties fulfill their obligations. They also provide a level of protection for the buyer by holding the earnest money until the transaction is complete.\n\nIn the case of your first home purchase, the escrow agent will be responsible for managing the escrow account, which includes your earnest money, until the closing date. They will also handle any other escrowed funds, such as property taxes and insurance premiums.",
